  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying Without Business Experience</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Sweden requires proven entrepreneurial track record. First-time business owners without prior self-employment are routinely rejected. You need documented history of running your own business.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Remote Work for Foreign Clients Only</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Sweden's permit is for business IN Sweden, not remote work FROM Sweden. If your business plan shows only foreign clients with no Swedish market activity, expect rejection. This isn't a digital nomad visa.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Processing Time</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">12-20 months is real. Don't quit your job, sell your house, or make irreversible plans until you have the approved permit. Many applicants underestimate this and face serious life disruption.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Insufficient Financial Proof</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">SEK 200,000+ must be demonstrated in bank statements. Loans, credit lines, or projected income don't count. You need liquid savings available now.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Weak Business Plan</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Generic business plans fail. Show specific Swedish market analysis, realistic financial projections, and clear explanation of why Sweden (not just "I want to live there"). Migrationsverket evaluates economic contribution seriously.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Sweden -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Sweden</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Sweden has universal healthcare funded through taxes. Once you have a personnummer and are registered in the population register (folkbokföring), you access the same system as Swedish citizens with minimal costs.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Access</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">After Registration (personnummer)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP visit: SEK 100-300 (~€9-26)</li>
          <li>✓ Annual cap: SEK 1,300 (~€115)</li>
          <li>✓ Specialist: SEK 200-400 (~€18-35)</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital: SEK 120/day max</li>
          <li>✓ Prescriptions: Capped SEK 2,600/year</li>
          <li>✓ Excellent quality nationwide</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Before Registration</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>△ Private insurance required</li>
          <li>△ Full costs upfront</li>
          <li>△ Emergency care always available</li>
          <li>△ 3-6 months until registration</li>
          <li>△ Budget €120-300/month insurance</li>
          <li>△ Same quality, different payment</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Swedish Healthcare Works</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare is managed by regions (regioner). You choose a vårdcentral (health center) as your primary care provider. Referrals needed for specialists. Wait times can be longer than private systems but care quality is high.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Private option:</strong> Some expats supplement with private insurance (€50-150/month) for faster access, English-speaking doctors, or private rooms. Companies like Skandia and Trygg-Hansa offer supplementary plans.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is processing 12-20 months?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Migrationsverket has significant backlogs and thoroughly evaluates business viability. They assess whether your business genuinely contributes to the Swedish economy. There's no way to expedite this—plan accordingly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work remotely for foreign clients?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The self-employment permit requires a Swedish business serving the Swedish market. Pure remote work for foreign clients doesn't qualify. Your business must have genuine Swedish economic activity. Consider Portugal or Estonia if you only want to serve foreign clients.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What type of company should I establish?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Most applicants use an aktiebolag (AB)—Swedish limited company. Requires SEK 25,000 share capital. You need 51%+ ownership. Enskild firma (sole proprietorship) is possible but AB is more common for immigration purposes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family join me?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes—spouse and children can apply for family residence permits. You need additional financial resources (SEK 100,000 per spouse, SEK 50,000 per child). Spouses get work rights in Sweden.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          4 years of continuous residence with self-employment permit. You must maintain your business and meet the original requirements throughout. After 5 years total residence, you can apply for Swedish citizenship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Sweden worth the wait and cost?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For the right person, yes. Sweden offers unmatched quality of life, world-class social benefits, safety, and a path to EU citizenship. But the 12-20 month wait, high costs, and strict requirements mean it's not for everyone. Be honest about whether you're truly committed to building a business in Sweden.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Sweden's Self-Employment Permit is not a digital nomad visa—it's a serious business immigration route for entrepreneurs committed to building in Sweden. The 12-20 month processing time, SEK 200,000+ financial requirement, and strict business experience criteria filter for genuinely committed applicants.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      What you get in return is access to one of the world's best societies: universal healthcare, generous parental leave, excellent education, safe cities, and a path to EU citizenship. Sweden doesn't do shortcuts—but it rewards those who commit fully.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      If you're looking for a quick, cheap way to work remotely in Europe, look elsewhere. But if you're ready to invest years building a genuine Swedish business and integrating into Swedish society, the payoff is substantial.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Sweden's self-employment permit is for serious entrepreneurs, not nomads. Budget €130-300/month for health insurance during the 3-6 month transition before joining Sweden's excellent public system. The long processing time and strict requirements mean this is a multi-year commitment—make sure Sweden is truly where you want to build your future.
      </p>
